segments.text: That's one of those things that the military shouldn't get into.
You mean it was too political?
Too political?
Yes.
I'll illustrate that.
I knew a good many Britishers, I guess, if you gather, and I knew what their point of view about it was, and that was expressed by their government to Truman directly.
No part of it.
They'd part company with us if they did it.

Of course, I knew that people thought that it would lead Russia into war, and us into war with Russia, and I knew the pros and cons of that, but these are not questions which military people should address themselves to.
What did you think of Truman's firing MacArthur?
He had to.
He had no option.
He had to.
MacArthur stepped over that line I was talking about.
Yeah.
Now, when were you assigned to the headquarters of Europe?
as commander of the light bomber wing in France.
Well, I served in Europe headquarters before that.
I was assigned there to help arrange to get what we now call tactical weapons into position and so forth and so forth.
And the opportunity came to get out of that headquarters into an active unit and I grabbed it.
And when was this, early 1950s?
I guess so.
Wait a minute, wasn't it 51?
I came back in 54, so it had to be 51.
Okay, so you were commander of the light bomber wing in France from 1951 to 1954?
Look, I spent six months roughly in Europe, I mean Europe headquarters, and two and a half years roughly in France.
So it had whatever that adds up to.
Was it at this time when you were promoted to a Brigadier General?
No, I wasn't promoted until I came home.
And about how large was the command?
It was a bomb wing.
It was the only one of its kind in NATO, but it was a pleasure, particularly because of the
It got me away from these things that I'm not too talented at anyway, away from the opposing forces and so on that I mentioned earlier.
At this time France of course was still in NATO and later on by 61 they were taken out of NATO.
How were the relations between the French and the Americans and the military?
Oh I'd say good.
It depended on where you were dealing.
The relations at the highest level were not very good because it was totally political.
The relations that I had with my counterparts in the French Air Force and the French Army were very good.
In fact, they were amicable.
I entertained them at my base in a goddamn lousy tent camp and they entertained me in their chateau.
But we were good friends and we got along well and both of us got something out of it.
But the relationships in the parish was something else because they were motivated a different way.
Now in this time when you were in France, the United States was trying to rejuvenate West Germany and they eventually joined NATO too and we re-armed or helped re-arm West Germany.
What was your opinion of re-arming West Germany?
My opinion was we better goddamn well do it if we wanted to defend Europe on that part of it.
Of course.
But you see, at the time we're fixed on here, that geography of France was a backdrop.
Now it's denied us.
But that's no reason to talk about that.
See, I went back to NATO after the next assignment and got another slant at it.
NATO is never going to be out of trouble.
I read the papers and almost every year there will be something about the drift in NATO or the schisms in NATO.
That's always the case and it always will be the case.
If you want to ask me whether or not I think the United States puts too much into it, as of right now I don't know.
When I was there we did put too much into it.
I mean by that we put more into it than we had to and it was extremely expensive.
Now you left the command of the light bomber wing.
This was your first wing command wasn't it?
Well I guess
This is the first tactical command I've had, yes.
How did you like that?
How did you like it?
Did you enjoy being a commander?
Of course I did.
As a matter of fact, the goddamn outfit still has reunions.
I had one not long ago.
And I will say this, see I remember one way in this
Goddamn sit around and tell the goddamn this lies.
They'll all act like now like they just had a wonderfully good time.
Well, Christ, it wasn't all that.
They were in the mud a lot.
And God knows their wives didn't enjoy it.
My wife joined me there later.
And she hated every day of it.
But those guys seemed to think that was a great experience.
I didn't worry at all.
See, we went everywhere.
Being the only one of our kind, we went all the way from Norway down to Saudi Arabia.
This had its disadvantages, but also for a flying machine type, it was pretty good.
And we'd go down to North Africa and bomb up the ranges and so forth.
I made myself very unpleasant and disliked, of course.
That's common for me.
because my guys had to carry around a handbag full of different kinds of currencies and stupid bastards over in Germany that never went anywhere.
They kept us on a funny money deal.
For quite a script-type money, you don't think you could buy a meal in Italy with it or anywhere else for that matter, except right on a base.
But it was hell's own job trying to get it through their heads that
They were the pain in the ass to us who had to move all the way across the theater.
The fighter outfits didn't.
See, they always came back to the home base right there.
And that was just one of the things that made me persona non grata, I guess.
But altogether, and as far as the experience, working with the Americans and with the French, it was good.
Do you think that your duty as the commander of that wing was one of the main reasons why you were promoted to generalship?
I don't know.
I want to make another philosophical statement about this.
When you're in the military, if you know how the system works, and I did,
Look, I've been in it a long time.
You don't bother about things like that.
The thing is, you've got one person to answer to, and that's yourself.
If you feel like you're doing all right and you're doing what's right, that's what counts.
And if you get promoted, fine.
You don't bother with it too much.
Unfortunately, most people aren't made that way.
They think there's something wrong with them.
And that's very painful.
But I never bothered about that.
I knew how the system worked.
Now, you went back to the United States as deputy for personnel tactical air command.
Was that a Pentagon job?
Oh, no.
No, it was headquartered then at Langley.
Okay, at Langley.
I want to make one more statement about this.
By the time I was promoted to general, God knows, there must have been probably 150 at least men who had been junior to me who were promoted before me.
But by the time I was promoted the second time, I was probably promoted over 300 men who were senior to me.
Did I make it clear why this thing doesn't make so goddamn much difference as most people seem to think it does?
Okay.
Now at Langley, or during, this is, your next assignment then was from about 1954 to about 1957, probably.
Four to 58, I believe it was.
Okay, to 1958.
Wait a minute, was it four years?
Must have been, that's what it was.
Now as it was during this time that the Strategic Air Command of course was glamorized in America.
There's even movies about it and Curtis LeMay was the leader
And I've heard from other Air Force officers that there was some contention between tactical and the strategic air commands.
Would you like to address that?
Some what?
There were some problems.
There was some irritants.
Oh, yes.
There was friction.
Yes, of course there was.
Would you?
Well, I'll illustrate it this way.
Back when I was in the training command in the same job, that time when
The Air Force was going to make a big program change, or change of any consequence.
They called in senior officers, various commands, and we were called in to look at the plan under which the Strategic Air Command was going to be established and run.
Two men in the conference, myself and one more,
said this is probably going to be a bomb idea.
But it may not be.
But one thing you can be sure of, and that is you're going to establish an Air Force within the Air Force, separate and distinct.
And that is going to cause you some problems.
And we went on back and exactly set up that way.
And what we said and how we did,
Whether it's justified or not, I'm not in a position to judge.
All I'm saying is that, yes, there were problems.
And when I got back to TAC, we inherited them.
It made for a situation in which you found yourself necessarily in competition with someone that you should not compete with.
That's still true.
You knew Curtis LeMay for a number of years before this time.
We were classmates in the flight school.
What did you think of him?
Probably the best air commander or combat situation we've ever had.
Not necessarily the attack.
There were two others that were just as good.
Who were they?
Pat Partridge and Opie Weiler.
LeMay was an extremely competent man.
Now, let me talk about it just a moment since you asked the question.
Way back when we were young in the service, each of us had to qualify as a radio operator, as a navigator, as an observer, as a gunner, as a pilot.
Of course, all of us were pilots.
When LeMay set out to do these things, he set out to be the best, to be the best radio operator, to be the best navigator, to be the best man with a gun and all that sort of thing.
And he pretty goddamn well achieved that.
I'll go one step further to illustrate what I mean.
When I checked in his headquarters before I joined the group which I flew with,
and fact-stated his headquarters there, so just to get the pitch.

When a first, a mission came in for debriefing, he was then what they called a wing commander, later called it a division, now they call it an air force, but when they came in, you do a debriefing, you get the story from, here's the lead pilot, here's the lead navigator, here's the gunner, here's the, and so forth.
Now, it was self-evident in the briefing that LeMay knew more about what these people were doing than they knew themselves.
That's pretty impressive.
He wasn't earnest about it.
It was just self-evident to anybody that knew anything about how you run a show like that.
He's pretty good.
He's got some god awful blind spots, but who doesn't?
He's good.
What did you think his blind spots were?
One of them, and this applies more earlier than it did later, but it applied at the time he took over the Air Force.
He wasn't
I don't know whether the right word is sensitive or whether he just planned to give it down, about the fact that people aren't all alike and they never will be.
He was pretty severe to some people that had a lot to contribute.
That's what I would call his mind spot, his principal one.
He mellowed in his later years, he mellowed quite a lot.
In fact, I'm reminded of a man who I knew pretty well that had gone to a commander's conference down in the Caribbean not too long after LeMay took over.
And he came back just like that.
God damn, I don't understand it.
He said, I used to be scared of that son of a bitch that I'd run and leave the room to avoid him.
He's just as kind and gentle as he can be.
The fact of the matter was, LeMay got what he wanted.
He didn't have to be that way anymore.
He's a good guy, and God knows, you don't find many like him.
I don't know anything about him now, I haven't seen him in years, but I suspect he's probably not in very good health.
Now the Tactical Air Command, was your mission training?
Well, not really.
Not just that.
Basically, in peacetime, that is your mission.
So I can't say, no, it wasn't.
Of course it is.
But we had to build up units.
We had to deploy them.
We had what they now call this rapid deployment force.
It's been in being a long time.
I don't know why the newspapers say it's brand new, but it isn't.
We had to get all this done, and then when the Air Force budget got cut, we had to cut it all back and readjust and all that.
I'm talking about the headquarters job.
And all the time, at least my job, was to see to it that the right people were in the right place.
It's rewarding, particularly
By that time, you see, I knew a hell of a lot of people.
I knew something about anybody, any colonel, for example, who might be coming into the command or leaving it.
If I didn't know him personally, I knew something about him.
And it's useful to even...
if necessary, to bend the rules a little bit to see to it that the right guy gets in the right place.
Everybody benefits, you know, when this happens.
He does, and the unit does, everybody does.
And when you get the wrong guy, so much for that.
It's a good type of job.
Okay.
Now your last job, you were assigned as Chief of Staff of the Allied Air Force in Southern Europe.
And so that was from 1958 to 1961.
At this time you were a two-star general?
Now, were relations with the French starting to sour?
You must have dealt quite a bit with NATO and the French.
Oh, the French kind of got on me for
what it did for them, I guess they liked me all right.
Did I hear your question?
I don't know what you, I'm not sure.
Were relations between, during these last three years from 58 to 61, were relations between the American Air Force and the French Air Force starting to sour?
That wasn't the way of it.
Oh, okay.
About the time I got back there, I mean got back to NATO, mind you I'd had to go back and forth
God knows how many times I've been in Europe while I was stationed at Langley.
I don't remember a lot on business.
So it wasn't totally unfamiliar with me, but about the time I got back, De Gaulle was just taking over.
And France was right on the verge of civil war.
I mean right on the brink of the civil war.
Or the Algerian affair.
Yes.
I know this because I had some friends of French officers who informed me of it.
It was close.
Now, the fact that de Gaulle wanted us out of France and France out of NATO had to do with his idea of the grandeur of France.
Now look, don't get me wrong, de Gaulle was a great man.
He was one of the great men of our century.
But he was great for France.
He didn't give batshit about the United States or Britain or Yugoslavia or anywhere.
It was la belle France.
And he did what he thought was right for France.
Maybe he's right, maybe he's wrong, I don't know.
The fact of the matter is that NATO as a fighting outfit is just about the same.
You're going to get about as much out of the French Air Force as you got when it was in NATO.
It's not going to be appreciably different.
So, I don't know how to answer your question.
Okay, okay.
What were your duties as Chief of Staff?
Damn little...
keeping the peace mainly.
I think, on retrospect, I thought, well, here's something, here's an old guy that we might as well give him a pleasant place to live for his last few years.
That may have been it.
But I came back to retire.
I wasn't doing anything worth much.
And I was told, God damn it, shut up and go on back.
And I found out, I guess, when I got back, that somebody in Punggol knew something I didn't, I guess.
And there was something to do, but it was quite different from what I had done in the past.
I think I did a good job, but as far as work, no.
I spent my time interested, when I found out I was going to have to stay out of my term, diving in the Mediterranean.
That was fascinating.
Scuba diving.
But in terms of duty, I guess the thing could be described as trying to prevent fires, trying to prevent problems from happening.
Dog simple.
Why'd you retire?
Why did you retire?
Well, officially I retired for physical disability, but actually I was coming up for mandatory retirement pretty quick anyway.
Were you ready to retire from the service?
Oh, yes.
Of course.
You see, there's a time for everything, as the poem says.
I'd lost my love affair with airplanes.
I flew them.
But damn business on the ground had gotten so complicated, and there was so much red tape, and I'm here, and I'm going to be there, and all this reporting to half a dozen stations.
It wasn't much fun for me anymore.
It was totally different from what I had started back when I had the love affair with airplanes.
That was in it.
And shoot, you don't want to stay in that kind of racket too long.
I don't mean by that I enjoy retirement.
I don't at all.
Never had.
Never expected.
I much preferred the active life that I had, but I certainly knew it was time to retire.
No question about that.
I'll make one more statement about Naito, and I'll illustrate it again.
Another guy from Texas A&M, he was one of my students in the flying school.
I've known him ever since.
He was a hell of a good man.
I came home and needed somebody to be my exec and asked him if he wanted the job.
He said he was delighted to get it.
So he brought his family over there.
The first thing I did, he came out of the Air War College, and I know what he'd been taught there.
Send him out to find out under what exact terms the nations in NATO would go to war.
And he came back shaking his head, and I can't believe it.
I did it on purpose.
This is a common sense guy that has to understand that he's an Alice in Wonderland situation.
It's through the looking glass.
You see it that way.
On this side, you see it the other way.
That's NATO.
That's the best simple explanation I can give for it.
What was his answer?
What did they say?
Every goddamn one of them has a different will.
Here's what the treaty says.
An attack on one is an attack on all.
The United States doesn't say that.
Neither does any other country in NATO.
That's what the treaty says.
Mm-hmm.
In some circumstances this would be true, in others it wouldn't.
That's NATO.
NATO as an intelligence situation couldn't be worse.
It's an absolute sieve.
Anything by way of an order, NATO order, is automatically available to the other side.
And you know this.
This is one of the things that you have to deal with.
But Larry Norstad is a genius.
He's an absolute genius.
Who is this now?
Norstad, who is the commander who's been in NATO ever since it started.
He's an absolute genius in understanding these things and coping with them.
I used to think,
all right, if we have a war, who's coming over to run the war?
And I had a pretty good idea.
It would have been either Partridge or Weiland, because Larry's genius does not extend to that particular type of duty, but for that duty, you couldn't have had a better man.
De Gaulle said as much.
I'm just trying to illustrate the nature of that type of duty.
Now let's talk a little bit about some major changes in the military that we've had over the last, well since the 1950s.
One was we, the military, and I'd just like your opinion on it.
I know that you weren't involved with a lot of these things, but that's all right.
I'd just like your opinion.
One was ending the Selective Service, the draft, and now having a volunteer army.
What do you think of that?
I'm sorry, but I have to give you my point of view.
That's what I want.
This is a political question.
A military person does his best to live with whatever the politicians give him.
To put it another way, there are advantages to both sides.
And you live with compromise, whatever the politicians say it should be.
There are obvious advantages to one or the other.
I've lived with both.
Mm-hmm.
What do you think of the increased number of women in the armed forces?
One of my best friends among the women in the service is the first woman to be head of the Air Women, Gina Holmes.
She was my diving partner in the Mediterranean.
If I was in a firefight, I'd just as soon have Gina as anybody I know.
That's about as high a compliment as I can give.
On the other hand, if it was a long slog out, she just simply doesn't have the physical stamina.
She'd deny that.
She's a good athlete, but this is a fact of life.
She has done more for the Air Force than anybody ever.
to increase utilization and the wider spread utilization of women in the Air Force.
Jeannie's retired, of course, but she's a major gentleman.
Well, she finished.
First one we ever had.
Boy, she's worth it.
I hope I'm making myself clear.
I don't want to call that gal down.
I say, if I was in a firefight, I'd just as soon have her as any man I've ever been with, and I've been with some damn good men.
But there's more to that.
Also, in a
complex staff situation, no problem with her.

The only problem I see with women in the service is this god-awful situation, you get him now and then, that requires a hell of a lot of physical stamina, and don't get me wrong, all men don't have it either.
Right.
So, that's about all I can say.
Okay.
What do you think about the
increased number of black Americans and integration of units in the service?
One of my best friends in the service, not really, but a very good friend in the service was Benno Davis, who was the first black general, finished as a lieutenant general.
One of the best men I've ever known.
Benno put his whole self on the line, his whole career, everything, on a
on a premise.
This is way back, not too long after the war.
You treat everybody alike regardless of his color.
Everybody takes the same exam.
Everybody takes the same requirement.
And the black men that can't hack it, get out.
The white men that can't hack it, get out.
Ben couldn't have been righter.
He's absolutely right.
As long as we in the Air Force were able to follow that, and mind you, it was a hell of a lot to overcome before we could.
And I was there.
We were in clover.
There was no such thing as a Negro problem.
Unfortunately, that couldn't last, because you know what happened.
The Civil Rights Program came along.
The laws were changed.
And the worst thing you can do
is to give a Negro soldier or a Jew soldier or a Spanish soldier an idea that he has certain rights because of his color.
That has happened, and it's a tragedy.
That's the worst feature of it.
As long as everybody is treated just the same, to the same standards, by God, you don't have a problem.
except, of course, with the ignorant bigots.
And you can't get rid of ignorant bigots.
You always have them.
But you can make them come to terms with it as long as they're all meeting the same standards.
But when somebody gets a special right that he shouldn't have, you've got trouble.
I'll illustrate that.
Hell, the place that I've set up, built, and commanded first,
Laredo before they closed it.

Had some Negroes, and this was since I retired, come into a mess hall and inhabit it just as though it was a mutiny and defy the people because they felt not that they were being discriminated out there, because they were discriminated in town.
Now, nobody has the right to come in and take over a mess hall.
If he's got a bitch, he's got a right to bitch.
But when that happened, the commander was unable to do what I would have done, and could have done, in the same circumstance.
He had to send for a negotiator, a negro, a master sergeant, assigned for that purpose at his headquarters to come down and negotiate with those men.
This ain't good.
I don't want to weigh in on that problem too much,
I've lived with it when it was a damn sight better.
It's pretty simple, once you can get people to get it through their heads and do it, to treat everybody just exactly alike.
Make them all meet the same standards for promotion, for pay, for rank, for whatever.
No problem.
There's the most unfortunate feature of it, which you're well aware of,

When you're dealing with very large numbers of people, you're going to find out that the IQ rating on a very large number, the lower ones are going to turn out to be Negroes, disproportionate to their numbers in the population.
I don't want to go into that because I know the exceptions to it.
People like Ben.
Ben is quite a man.
The other one who reached high regard, his dad died of a heart attack, used to command the Air Defense Command, Chappie, Chappie James.
He was a four-star general when he retired.
That was the man that saved him and put him on the right track.
Chappie was a damn good man, too.
But when he was a wheeler-dealer radical, he had to get straightened out and
learned that he had to live to the same standards that other people did.
Ben taught him that.
By God, look what happened.
He ended up as a four-star general.
So this can be done.
There's no Negro problem if you treat everybody alike.
The problem comes up when you start elevating a white man because he's white or elevating a black man because he's black.
That's where the problem is.
But I don't think this country is going to change about that.
Let's drop it.
Okay.
Let's go to leadership.
Oh, that's the word that military people use the most and nobody can define.
I know what I think it is.
What do you think it is?
I've already described it.
It's what I learned down in ROTC.
That's what I think.
But there comes a time
When it means something else.
When it means something else.
Something you don't learn in A&M.
What time is that?
At a higher rank.
Well what does it mean then?
What does it mean then?
Yeah, at higher rank.
It means a different kind of talent.
It means an ability to
to deal with your peers, not with your subordinates, because leadership is generally thought of as being able to deal with and lead your subordinates.
But leadership in the higher ranks means an ability to deal with your peers and to, as it were, lead them whether or not they want to be led.
And it's quite a different proposition.
think, I don't know whether that observation did any good.
Now let's talk a little bit, final topic here.
Let's talk a little bit about the changes over the last 20 years at Texas A&M.
Now I know you weren't involved with those changes, but you must have some opinions on them.
For example, we ended the mandatory Corps of Cadets.
Do you think that's good or bad for A&M?
What's your opinion?
The difference was good or bad or not, it had to be done.
I can speak a little bit on this, because I was working for that Governor Connelly's commission at the time.
This had to be done.
And one of the men I admired beyond reason was Earl Rudder.
I don't think anybody else could have done it.
Earl Rudder had to do that, and he had to see to it that the women got in there.
Both of those things had to be done.
All you had to do was to lay out the problem, which is what I was helping to do.
I was dismayed, I must admit, but Rudder was in no way dismayed.
He knew what had to be done.
He did it.
If he hadn't been the kind of man he was, A&M would have had hell.
I'm very much admired.
Sorry he's dead.
What was your role in that?
What was your role in that?
Nothing really.
I was trying to get things together for the commission.
In the process I learned some things I'd rather not know.
In fact that was one of them.
I didn't realize until I began to deal with this that
NM was as far behind the times as it was.
And I didn't realize, see, my, if I know anything much, it's how to deal with figures.
For example, I deal with the stock market now, and that's the easiest way to make money I've ever run across, honestly.
I know what cost effectiveness is because I do.
I was really shocked to see what the cost-effectiveness factor of Texas A&M was when I got into it.
And the things that Rudder did had to be done because of that.
There's no other reason.
I thought, because I was in it, that the old ROTC system at A&M was good.
You couldn't do it.
You couldn't do it and discharge your responsibilities to the people of the state of Texas.
Do you follow me?
Yeah.
That's why it had to be done.
I won't argue the good or bad features of it had to be done.
Same with allowing women and blacks into Texas.
Same thing.
Same thing.
hope, and it's nothing but hope, that the scholastic standards can be kept up.
I don't really know.
You see, when I went there, you got a tremendous influx every fall, and then they start going home, just like that.
In other words, the law required that they take them, but the law didn't require that they keep them.
When the guy got out of there, whether he was in animal husbandry or whether he was in civil engineering, you knew goddamn well he knew certain things that you had to know or he didn't get out.
I hope that's still true.
It can be, but it depends.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I just don't know anything about the school now.
I hope so.
I think probably so, but that's a guess.
What little bit I'm able to gather from the various reports I read.
You're in a better fix to answer that question than I am.
Well, I'm about exhausted the questions that I have.
No, I meant whether or not the standards of the institution are still high.
I think they are.
Hope so.
I think we just raised the entrance standards.
I heard that.
Back then, you see, they didn't have the entrance standard problem.
Say, I've got one more thing that goes back a long way.
It has to do with the education and the military person.
I had a contemporary who was a little bit ahead of me in flying school who became
One of the Air Force's best aeronautical engineers.
You would never guess that he graduated from East Texas State Teacher's College.
You know goddamn well they didn't teach him anything about that.
But when he died, he was crashed, of course.
He was on his way to command that test facility out there at Edwards.
And there's no flies on him.
He learned what he had to learn in the Air Force, I mean about the technology.
So it ain't necessarily so that you have to get a lot of this crammed in your head in college.
Okay, finish.
Well, I'm done with the questions.
Is there something else that you... No, God almighty, I'm sorry I kept you so long.
No, is there something about your career that I might have missed?
No, I think you covered more of it than you should have.
Okay.
